> > their line representation should be "finalized" before allowing user to manipulate the text inside the buffer. Which also (usually) means computing icons for all entries.
> 
> Surely icons can be non-editable decorations in the buffer. I would consider it a bad user experience otherwise.

I am glad I've got to read your opinion on this topic. Thanks for sharing!

> > entries need to be computed with their icon before being suggested to the user as a picker entry
> 
> This sounds like a design problem.

As far as I understand, this is indeed the *consequence* of the main decision about doing all the work in the separate process. Doesn't mean it is not worth taking into account.

------

What *is* a design problem, is the presence of non-avoidable slow-ish step of string pattern matching during filetype detection. Removing it completely is not possible as it it is needed for compatibility with Vim detection. Hence the suggestion for this option in a function that was exported specifically for user convenience. As it:
- Trivially and transparently affects code only in 3 `if` statements;
- Has proved *significant* effect on speed;
- Has test coverage;
- Has demand;
- *Needs* to be done in core;

... I am somewhat baffled to receive such a pushback.

> Use cases I currently know/care about all involve computing filetype based solely on the filename.

I would be warmer to providing some API that doesn't touch the filesystem. IO is horribly slow, relative to non-IO code, and touching the file system in hot loops should generally be avoided. That would at least give a `fast` option a much more objective and simpler definition.

That doesn't mean the use cases described here can't be avoided by approaching the problems differently.

> - Trivially and transparently affects code only in 3 if statements;

The concerns here aren't about implementation. It's not difficult to add a whole heap of niche flags to functions without incurring much implementation cost. The issue is that these flags are very niche, and haven't been well justified.

> - Has proved significant effect on speed;

Again, performance for the sake of performance, and at the cost of correctness.

> - Has test coverage;

Tests need to be maintained like anything else.

> - Has demand;

That's not how this works. Just having demand isn't enough. And the actual requirement is dubious and a bit XY.

> - Needs to be done in core;

Arguably doesn't need to be done at all.
